----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Table
tr -> table row, th -> table header, td -> table data
border-spacing: 30px; -> used for spacing between borders. If border is already collpased as below example, then we can't use this aS double border is removed.
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<style>
table, th, td {
  border:1px solid black;
  border-collapse: collapse; -> to avoid double borders
  background-color: #96D4D4; -> bg color of each cell
  border-radius: 10px; -> rounded cells
  border-style: dashed -> type of border like ridge, groove, inset, outset
}
</style>
<body>

<h2>A basic HTML table</h2>

<table style="width:100%">
  <tr>
    <th>Company</th>
    <th>Contact</th>
    <th>Country</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Alfreds Futterkiste</td>
    <td>Maria Anders</td>
    <td>Germany</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Centro comercial Moctezuma</td>
    <td>Francisco Chang</td>
    <td>Mexico</td>
  </tr>
</table>

Set width of column and rows height
<table style="width:100%">
  <tr style="height:200px">
    <th style="width:70%">Firstname</th>
    <th>Lastname</th>
    <th>Age</th>
  </tr>
  
Vertical tables
  <table style="width:100%">
  <tr>
    <th>Firstname</th>
    <td>Jill</td>
    <td>Eve</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <th>Lastname</th>
    <td>Smith</td>
    <td>Jackson</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <th>Age</th>  
    <td>50</td>
    <td>94</td>
  </tr>
</table>

merge cells Header for multiple column -> colspan
merge cells HEADER for multiple rows -> rowspan
<tr>
  <th rowspan="2">Phone</th>
  <td>555-1234</td>
</tr>

<table>
<tr>
    <th colspan="2">Name</th>
    <th>Age</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Jill</td>
    <td>Smith</td>
    <td>50</td>
</tr>
</table>
-------------------
Horizontal alternate stripes
To style every other table row element, use the :nth-child(even) selector like this:

tr:nth-child(even) {
  background-color: #D6EEEE;
}

Vertical alternate stripes
td:nth-child(even), th:nth-child(even) {
  background-color: #D6EEEE;
}
----------------------------
border at bottom only
tr {
  border-bottom: 1px solid #ddd;
}
------------------------------
Hover table elements
tr:hover {background-color: #D6EEEE;}
---------------------------
Caption heading for entire table
Note: <caption> tag should be inserted immediately after the <table> tag.
<table style="width:100%">
  <caption>Monthly savings</caption>
  <tr>
    <th>Month</th>
    <th>Savings</th>
  </tr>
</table>
---------------------------------------------------
colgroup
to color elements based on group of columns.
<table style="width: 100%;">
<colgroup>
  <col span="3"> -> empty colgroup makes no color
  <col span="2" style="background-color: #D6EEEE"> -> makes color with column 4-5
  <col span="3" style="background-color: pink">    -> makes color with column 6-7-8
  <col span="3" style="visibility: collapse">      -> hide colums 9-10-11
</colgroup>
<tr>
<colgroup> tag must be a child of a <table> element and should be placed before any other table elements, like <thead>, <tr>, <td> etc., but after the <caption> element, if present.
-----------------------------------------------------
HTML element
An HTML element is defined by a start tag, some content, and an end tag. Mostly, nested elements are +nt in document

EMPTY elements
HTML elements with no content are called empty elements.
The <br> tag defines a line break, and is an empty element without a closing tag:
<p>This is a <br> paragraph with a line break.</p>

<hr> element
The <hr> element is used to separate content in an HTML page:
<h1>This is heading 1</h1>
<p>This is some text.</p>
<hr>
<h2>This is heading 2</h2>
<p>This is some other text.</p>

<pre>
preformatted text, holds spaces and line breaks.
<pre>
  My Bonnie lies over the ocean.

  My Bonnie lies over the sea.
</pre>

Attributes
Provides additonal info to elements.
<img src="w3schools.jpg" alt="W3Schools.com" width="104" height="142">
alt attribute for the <img> tag specifies an alternate text for an image

Style attribute
<p style="color:red;">This is a red paragraph.</p>
<h1 style="font-size:60px;">Heading 1</h1>
Style properties:
1. background-color
CSS background-color property defines the background color for an HTML element.
<body style="background-color:powderblue;">
</body>
2. font-family
CSS font-family property defines the font to be used for an HTML element:
<h1 style="font-family:verdana;">This is a heading</h1>
3. font-size
font-size property defines the text size for an HTML element:
<h1 style="font-size:300%;">This is a heading</h1>
4. text-align
CSS text-align property defines the horizontal text alignment for an HTML element:
<h1 style="text-align:center;">Centered Heading</h1>


Lang attribute
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<body>
</body>

Title attribute
The title attribute defines some extra information about an element.
Displayed when we hover over the element.
<p title="I'm a tooltip">This is a paragraph.</p>

<abbr> tag
defines an abbreviation or an acronym. add dotted underline over text.
<p>The <abbr title="World Health Organization">WHO</abbr> was founded in 1948.</p>

We can remove underline by making
text-decoration:none;

<b> element
defines bold text, without any extra importance
<b>This text is bold</b>

<strong> element
defines text with strong importance
<strong> This text is important!</strong>

<i> italic
<i>This text is italic</i>

<em> emphasized tag
writes in italic but read verbally stressed
<p><em>This text is emphasized.</em></p>
<p><i>This text is emphasized.</i></p>

<small> element
defines smaller text
<small>This is some smaller text.</small>

<mark> element
defines text that should be marked or highlighted
<p>Do not forget to buy <mark>milk</mark> today.</p>

<del> element
defines text that has been deleted from a document. browser will cut the word.
<p>My favorite color is <del>blue</del> red.</p>

<ins> element
defines a text that has been inserted into a document. Browsers will usually underline inserted text
<p>My favorite color is <del>blue</del> <ins>red</ins>.</p>

<sub> element
defines subscript text. Subscript text appears half a character below the normal line
<p>This is <sub>subscripted</sub> text.</p>

<sup> element
defines superscript text. Superscript text appears half a character above the normal line
<p>This is <sup>superscripted</sup> text.</p>

<blockquote> element
defines a section that is quoted from another source. Browsers usually indent <blockquote> elements.
<blockquote cite="http://www.worldwildlife.org/who/index.html">
For 60 years, WWF has worked to help people and nature thrive. As the world's leading conservation organization, WWF works in nearly 100 countries. At every level, we collaborate with people around the world to develop and deliver innovative solutions that protect communities, wildlife, and the places in which they live.
</blockquote>

<q> tag
 defines a short quotation.
<p>WWF's goal is to: <q>Build a future.</q></p> -> "Build a future"

<address> element
usually renders in italic, and browsers will always add a line break before and after the <address> element.
<address>
Written by John Doe.<br>
Visit us at:<br>
</address>

<cite> tag
defines the title of a creative work (e.g. a book, a poem, etc. make it in italic
<p><cite>The Scream</cite> by Edvard Munch. Painted in 1893.</p>

<bdo> tag
is used to override the current text direction:
<bdo dir="rtl">This text will be written from right to left</bdo>

<!-- comments -->

border property
<h1 style="border:2px solid Tomato;">Hello World</h1>

5 color codes -> rgb, hsla, rgba, hsla, hex
<h1 style="background-color:rgb(255, 99, 71);">...</h1>
<h1 style="background-color:#ff6347;">...</h1>
<h1 style="background-color:hsl(9, 100%, 64%);">...</h1>
<h1 style="background-color:rgba(255, 99, 71, 0.5);">...</h1>
<h1 style="background-color:hsla(9, 100%, 64%, 0.5);">...</h1> 
